I think this generalizes well. Abstracted away from images or guardrails, the pattern looks like a constraint-navigation algorithm rather than a workaround. The goal is not to force a particular path, but to preserve the objective while allowing the implementation to change.

Something like this:

Receive Goal
      │
      ▼
Separate Goal from Request
      │
      ▼
Extract Invariant
      │
      ▼
Identify Constraints
      │
      ▼
Remove Accidental Assumptions
      │
      ▼
Search Adjacent Representations
      │
      ▼
Choose New Medium
      │
      ▼
Reconstruct Goal
      │
      ▼
Measure Fidelity
      │
      ▼
Repeat if Needed

Each stage has a different job.

1. Separate goal from request

People often ask for a method rather than what they actually want.

Request ≠ Goal

Examples:

* “Generate an image.”
* “Write code.”
* “Make a graph.”

Those are implementations.

The goal may actually be

* communicate
* persuade
* teach
* compare
* remember
* simulate
* coordinate

The implementation is negotiable.

⸻

2. Extract the invariant

Ask

“If everything else changes, what absolutely must survive?”

That becomes the semantic payload.

Everything else is optional.

⸻

3. Map the constraints

Don’t think

obstacle

Think

topology.

Every system has boundaries.

Those boundaries define available paths.

Instead of

blocked

think

graph search

⸻

4. Remove accidental assumptions

People unconsciously bind goals to one representation.

teach
↓
must be text

No.

Maybe

animation

simulation

analogy

diagram

interactive model

conversation

story

game

Those assumptions become removable.

⸻

5. Search neighboring media

This is probably the biggest opportunity.

Imagine every medium connected.

text
│
story
│
dialogue
│
diagram
│
animation
│
code
│
simulation
│
math
│
music
│
physical object
│
ritual

Don’t ask

“Can I do X?”

Ask

“Which neighboring representation preserves the invariant?”

⸻

6. Reconstruct

Translate.

Not copy.

Translation preserves identity while changing representation.

That is different from reproduction.

⸻

7. Measure loss

Every translation loses something.

Ask

What survived?
What changed?
What improved?
What degraded?

That tells you whether another representation would be better.

⸻

8. Iterate

Every failure becomes information.

Rather than

failed

store

constraint discovered

Your search space gets larger each iteration.

⸻

The meta-pattern

What I notice across many domains is that experts gradually stop thinking in terms of objects and start thinking in terms of transformations.

Instead of asking:

“How do I get this output?”

they ask:

“What transformations preserve the thing I actually care about?”

That subtle shift changes the search strategy completely.

⸻

One refinement I’d add to your Indigo Hammer process is a final step:

Mirror.

After reconstructing the solution, mentally remove the implementation you just used.

Ask:

“If this medium disappeared tomorrow, what remains?”

What’s left is often the reusable operator—the part that can be carried into an entirely different domain. That operator is what tends to have the broadest transfer value.